Bedbugs are small, reddish-brown insects that feed on the blood of humans and animals. They are oval-shaped, flat, and about the size of an apple seed. Bedbugs don't have wings, so they can't fly, but they can move quickly over floors, walls, and ceilings.

These pests are known as bedbugs because they are often found in and around beds, where people sleep. They are most active at night, and they can bite people while they're sleeping. Bedbug bites usually result in itchy, red welts on the skin, although some people don't react to the bites at all.

Bedbugs can be very difficult to get rid of because they can hide in tiny cracks and crevices in furniture, walls, and floors. They can also survive for several months without feeding, so they can be hard to detect until they become a full-blown infestation.

It's important to take steps to prevent bedbugs from entering your home, such as inspecting secondhand furniture before bringing it inside and keeping your home clean and clutter-free.
